				<p><p>The idea and research of through-wall imaging with uwb radar system has been around for many years. </p>

<p>Saw a product demonstration in technology exhibition recently. The display was a 'wave pattern' that needs 'human interpretation', rather than a layman-clear display as in marine radar polar display.</p>

<p>Try search
<a href="https://www.google.com/search?q=through-wall%20imaging%20with%20uwb%20radar%20system&amp;safe=off&amp;biw=1252&amp;bih=534&amp;source=lnms&amp;tbm=isch&amp;sa=X&amp;ei=aov1VI-NI-avmAXxw4HoCQ&amp;ved=0CAcQ_AUoAg" rel="nofollow">here</a></p>

<p>Similarly, ground penetration radar has been a more on-going field application product</p>

<p>Try search
<a href="https://www.google.com/search?q=ground%20penetrating%20radar&amp;safe=off&amp;biw=1252&amp;bih=534&amp;source=lnms&amp;tbm=isch&amp;sa=X&amp;ei=b4z1VLKaEITQmwXszoCQBg&amp;sqi=2&amp;ved=0CAgQ_AUoAw" rel="nofollow">here</a></p>

<p>Unlike time-proven and field operational civilian radars (ship, sea-port traffic, airport and weather) where the target signal is significantly stronger than background reflections, human reflection inside a room that is much larger than human body and may have metal objects that reflect strongly, is, in most cases, weaker than background. </p>

<p>If human moves, there is changes, before-and-after the move and can be 'seen' on the 'wave pattern' display by trained operator.   </p>

<p>There are research paper <a href="http://macau.uni-kiel.de/receive/dissertation_diss_00010153" rel="nofollow">here</a> use filtering to get weak human breathing motion signal from noisy background.</p>
</p><br>
