				<p><p>A static human is well shielded by a wall.  Very long wave IR may pass a diffuse heat signature. The sound of breathing or exhaled CO2 may locate someone hiding in a wardrobe. </p>

<p>Micropower Impulse Radar or similar modern implementations for occupancy sensors that are used for turning on lights may work through walls a little but I believe they are Doppler based so need to have movement to detect a person.</p>

<p>The following light fitting incorporates a person sensor and they work through doors, operate at 5GHz and have a ~12mm long antenna on a shielded electronics module inside.</p>

